docs.abstract: The change by the Trump administration applies to many nonprofit organizations that are active in politics, and was praised by conservatives.
docs.snippet: The change by the Trump administration applies to many nonprofit organizations that are active in politics, and was praised by conservatives.
docs.lead_paragraph: The Trump administration will end a longstanding requirement that certain nonprofit organizations disclose the names of large donors to the Internal Revenue Service, a move that will allow some political groups to shield their sources of funding from government scrutiny.

headline.main: I.R.S. Will No Longer Force Kochs and Other Groups to Disclose Donors
headline.print_headline: I.R.S. Will No Longer Require Certain Nonprofits to Disclose Large Donors

byline.original: By Patricia Cohen, Kenneth P. Vogel and Jim Tankersley

docs.abstract: Andrew R. Wheeler, the agency’s new boss, appears to be ushering in a change in style, even as he maintains his commitment to his predecessor’s environmental policies.
docs.snippet: Andrew R. Wheeler, the agency’s new boss, appears to be ushering in a change in style, even as he maintains his commitment to his predecessor’s environmental policies.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The Environmental Protection Agency’s new boss, Andrew R. Wheeler, has unlocked the entrance to the third-floor administrator’s suite — which had been closed tight during the tenure of his predecessor, Scott Pruitt. Mr. Wheeler, who started Monday after Mr. Pruitt’s resignation, has also reduced his security detail and provided faster public updates to his daily schedule of events.

headline.main: ‘You Can’t Lead Unless You Listen,’ New E.P.A. Chief Says, Signaling Break From Pruitt
headline.print_headline: New E.P.A. Chief Rejects Pruitt’s Management Style, but Not His Policies

docs.abstract: Speaker Paul D. Ryan took the helm to heal a fractured Republican Party. He will leave in January with fault lines still visible, this time drawn by President Trump.
docs.snippet: Speaker Paul D. Ryan took the helm to heal a fractured Republican Party. He will leave in January with fault lines still visible, this time drawn by President Trump.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Paul D. Ryan took the helm of the House two and a half years ago, not because he wanted it, but because he was seen as the only lawmaker who could keep Republicans from devouring themselves. They had shut down the government, nearly precipitated a debt crisis and toppled a speaker, John A. Boehner.

headline.main: Ryan Found Himself on the Margins as G.O.P. Embraces Trump
headline.print_headline: For Ryan, Tax Cut Is Feather in His Cap, Trump an Albatross Around His Neck

byline.original: By Sheryl Gay Stolberg and Thomas Kaplan

docs.abstract: The women, who were contemporaries at the Naval Academy, are part of a powerful wave of political activism in the era of President Trump.
docs.snippet: The women, who were contemporaries at the Naval Academy, are part of a powerful wave of political activism in the era of President Trump.
docs.lead_paragraph: NORFOLK, Va. — Elaine Luria commanded an assault ship with a crew of 400 that patrolled the Persian Gulf for hostile Iranian vessels. Amy McGrath was the first female Marine to fly in an F-18 fighter jet in combat, dropping bombs over Afghanistan and Iraq. Mikie Sherrill was certified as a Navy helicopter pilot only after passing an underwater crash simulation in which she was blindfolded, turned upside down, and forced to find the sole exit door.

headline.main: From Annapolis to Congress? These Three Women Know Tough Missions
headline.print_headline: 3 Women Trying Annapolis Route to Congress

docs.abstract: Younger voters typically do not cast ballots in midterm elections. But after the Parkland, Fla., shooting, registration among younger voters is accelerating.
docs.snippet: Younger voters typically do not cast ballots in midterm elections. But after the Parkland, Fla., shooting, registration among younger voters is accelerating.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The pace of new voter registrations among young people in crucial states is accelerating, a signal that school shootings this year — and the anger and political organizing in their wake — may prove to be more than ephemeral displays of activism.

headline.main: Young People Keep Marching After Parkland, This Time to Register to Vote
headline.print_headline: Youths Keep Marching After Parkland, This Time Toward the Ballot Box

byline.original: By Michael Tackett and Rachel Shorey

docs.abstract: Republicans in Congress, dragged down by President Trump’s low approval ratings, are retiring in large numbers rather than seek re-election, a sign of trouble.
docs.snippet: Republicans in Congress, dragged down by President Trump’s low approval ratings, are retiring in large numbers rather than seek re-election, a sign of trouble.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Republicans in Congress, including several powerful committee chairmen, are rushing to retire rather than face re-election in the fall, a clear recognition that President Trump’s low approval rating will be a heavy weight on the party even with an improving economy.

headline.main: Republican Retirements Raise Talk of Democratic Wave in November
headline.print_headline: G.O.P. Braces for a Wave of Retiring Republicans

docs.abstract: A special election for a House seat in Ohio will test the power of the rural vote against the kind of affluent, rapidly growing suburbs that Democrats need to win.
docs.snippet: A special election for a House seat in Ohio will test the power of the rural vote against the kind of affluent, rapidly growing suburbs that Democrats need to win.
docs.lead_paragraph: NEW ALBANY, Ohio — There was a pitiable chance of success when Danny O’Connor knocked on Tami Halliday’s door Thursday morning to ask for her vote. All the data showed that Mr. O’Connor, a Democrat running in an August special election for a House seat here, was all but wasting his time.

headline.main: Door-Knocking Democrat Tries to Break G.O.P. Grip in Ohio Special Election
headline.print_headline: Door-Knocking Democrat Tries to Break G.O.P. Grip in Ohio

docs.abstract: Greg Pence, the vice president’s brother, is mounting something of a stealth campaign, years after leading a chain that went bankrupt and being sued over personal debts.
docs.snippet: Greg Pence, the vice president’s brother, is mounting something of a stealth campaign, years after leading a chain that went bankrupt and being sued over personal debts.
docs.lead_paragraph: COLUMBUS, Ind. — When you have the best known name in your congressional district and your younger brother is a heartbeat away from the presidency, it is difficult to run a stealth campaign. But Greg Pence is doing a pretty good job of it.

headline.main: As Another Pence Runs for Congress, His Business Record Raises Questions
headline.print_headline: Thorny Business Past May Test A Quiet Run by Pence’s Brother
